%T A273165 4,2,2,3,3,2,2,2,2,2,6,2,2,2,2,2,2,4,2,3,2,4,3,2,2,4,2,2,2,2,3,2,4,2,
%U A273165 2,4,4,2,3,4,6,3,2,2,2,2,3,2,3,2,2,4,2,5,3,2
%N A273165 One half the number of divisors of nonprime numbers that are 3 (mod 4).
%C A273165 With the Jan 05 2004 Jovovic comment on A078703 a(n) is also the number of divisors +1 as well as -1 (mod 4) of A091236(n). See the example section of A273164.
%H A273165 Amiram Eldar, <a href="/A273165/b273165.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%F A273165 a(n) = A000005(A091236(n))/2.
%F A273165 Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) ~ (log(n) + 2*gamma - 1 + 4*log(2))*n/4, where gamma is Euler's constant (A001620). - _Amiram Eldar_, Mar 10 2026
%t A273165 DivisorSigma[0, Select[4 * Range[0, 150] + 3, !PrimeQ[#] &]] / 2 (* _Amiram Eldar_, Mar 10 2026 *)
%o A273165 (PARI) list(lim) = apply(x -> numdiv(x)/2, select(x -> x%4 == 3 && !isprime(x), vector(lim, i, i))); \\ _Amiram Eldar_, Mar 10 2026
%Y A273165 Row lengths of A273164.
%Y A273165 Cf. A000005, A001620, A078703, A091236.
